<br>
Their stomachs pleasently full of good food and warming drinks, the three travellors moved off from the small Inn, back among the trees.  Snoww and Iztariani stood watchfully near Magpye as the small druidess cast a complicated spell, then the three faded from view in a sparkle of blue stars.<br>
<br>
Miles to the west, they reappeared at a great circle of ancient stones.  They had reached Northern Karana, the further point west that they could conveniently travel to Halas from.  Again Magpye worked her magics, speeding the feet of the weary travellors for the long run west and north.  The tall figure of Iztariani in the lead, two diminuitive shadows dogging her heels, they sped westwards under the darkening skies, their breath forming white plumes in the frosty autumn air.<br>
<br>
They ran in silence, a silence born of long companionship.  Just the occasional soft murmer drew attention to some interestign feature as they ran...an aged treant momentarily silouetted against the moon on a decent ridge, fields of grain cut and raked into neat sheaves, a family of great rolly-polly bears rooting in the undergrowth for a few last mouthfulls to pad their well-fattened bodies even further for the long winter ahead.<br>
<br>
Occasionally they stopped, just long enough to swallow a few mouthfulls of water and a bit of smoked meat, then would resume their westwards trek.<br>
<br>
It was an hour or two short of dawn then they finally traveled through the pass in the hills between the Karanas and the hilly country north of Qeynos.  As they once again stopped and gulped some water, Iztariani looked around thoughtfully.<br>
<br>
&quot;We've made good time tonight,&quot; she observed. &quot;I think we can slow our pace a little.  We should be able to make Everfrost by dawn, and Halas not long after.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;That's good,&quot; Magpye yawned.  &quot;I am soooo tired.  I just want to curl up and sleep for hours!&quot;<br>
<br>
Iztariani smiled down fondly at her small friend.  &quot;And I, too...but we must make it there before its too late.  Rest can come later.&quot;<br>
<br>
Wordlessly, Snoww climbed back to her feet and adjusted her backpack.  The others followed her example, and started north, their pace only slightly slower then before.<br>
<br>
Behind them, glowing red eyes opened in the darkness of the undergrowth near where thet'd been, and a silent form scrambled soundlessly after them, ears pricked and muzzle raised to follow their scent on the still nigth air.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE CENTER START--><center> - - - - -</center><!--EZCODE CENTER END--><br>
<br>
The group eyes the giant gnoll head carved in the cliff, and made sure their weapons were readily accessible before entering the darkend cave of the mouth.  Passing through Blackburrow should not present too many difficulties to travellors of their experience...but it was always better to be prepared.<br>
<br>
The long twisting tunnel eventually led them to a small cup in the mountain, open to the sky but surrounded by unclimbable walls.  A great natural well led downwards to a still, dark pond, distant torchlight in the depths of the great hole glinting feebly off its rippled surface.<br>
<br>
Magpye looked nervously around.  She, like many others, had spent time here in her youth fighting back the gnolls, even down into their maze of subterranean tunnels, and had bitter memories of the time...of companions lost, and slow-healing injuries from the filthy bites of the vicious creatures.  Singly, they were often great cowards...but in packs, they could be terrible foes.<br>
<br>
Snoww looked around curiously.  She, unlike the others, had never fought here.  As she looked around, movement near one of the great trees caught her eye...a young gnoll was crouched there, staring terrified at her and her companions.  Realising she's spotted it, it turned and dived into the undergrowth.<br>
<br>
&quot;Hey!&quot; she exclaimed, and dived after it.<br>
<br>
&quot;No!&quot; cried Magpye and Iztariani, but it was too late...she'd plunged right into a cleverly concealed trap at the base of the tree, and found herself falling a great distance, ending with a painful splash into a pool oc icy water.  Choking, she struggled to the surface of the subterranean pool, only to find a strong current pulling her off to one side and down a stone chute.  In the flickering torchlight, she glimpsed gnolls pacing along paths bordering the water, and peering down at it from a wooden bridge overhead.  The water dumped her into another pond, seemingly bottomless...she could feel the currents trying to pull her down, down beneath the earth.  Trying to move noislessly as possible, she paddled to the sandy banks and pulled herself out.  Before she could move, a heavy paw stepped on her back, pushing her down against the sand, and a deep growl reverberated from the massive gnoll standing over her.<br>
<br>
She was lost and surrounded, somewhere in the depth of the gnoll's stronghold.  She could only hope that Magye and Iztariani knew where she was, and could find her.<br>
